---
import BlogPostLayout from "@/layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro";
import { SITE } from "@data/constants";
import { blogAuthorJsonLd, getBlogPostBySlug } from "@data/blogPosts";
import coverUrl from "./whiteboard.png?url";
import presentationUrl from "./presentation.png?url"

const slug = "aph-hackathon-to-implementation";
const listing = getBlogPostBySlug(slug);
const author = listing?.author ?? "DPIN Team";
const pubDate = listing?.pubDate ?? new Date("2026-03-15");

const pageTitle = `From Hackathon to Implementation: How APH Accelerated a Municipal AI Concept | ${SITE.title}`;
const metaDescription =
  "How the Amsterdam Policy Hackathon moved beyond ideas to influence real policy practice — and what happened when a winning team's AI concept entered active development at the Municipality of Amsterdam.";
const canonicalUrl = `${SITE.url.replace(/\/$/, "")}/blog/${slug}/`;
---

<BlogPostLayout
  slug={slug}
  pageTitle={pageTitle}
  customDescription={metaDescription}
  customOgTitle={pageTitle}
  structuredData={{
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BlogPosting",
    headline: "From Hackathon to Implementation: How APH Accelerated a Municipal AI Concept",
    description: metaDescription,
    datePublished: pubDate.toISOString(),
    author: blogAuthorJsonLd(author),
    publisher: {
      "@type": "Organization",
      name: SITE.title,
      url: SITE.url,
    },
    mainEntityOfPage: { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": canonicalUrl },
    url: canonicalUrl,
    inLanguage: "en-US",
  }}
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-4 pb-16 pt-12 lg:max-w-3xl lg:px-6">
    <header class="text-center">
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
        <span class="font-medium text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-300"
          >By {author}</span
        >
        <span class="mx-2 text-neutral-300 dark:text-neutral-600" aria-hidden="true"
          >·</span
        >
        <time datetime={pubDate.toISOString()}>
          {
            pubDate.toLocaleDateString("en-US", {
              year: "numeric",
              month: "long",
              day: "numeric",
            })
          }
        </time>
      </p>
      <h1
        class="mt-2 text-balance text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200 md:text-4xl md:leading-tight"
      >
        From Hackathon to Implementation: How APH Accelerated a Municipal AI Concept
      </h1>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-3 max-w-2xl text-pretty text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400">
        One of the core questions behind the Amsterdam Policy Hackathon is whether
        a hackathon can move beyond ideas and actually influence policy practice.
        Our collaboration with the Municipality of Amsterdam suggests that it can.
      </p>
    </header>

    <figure class="mt-10 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 dark:border-neutral-700">
      <img
        src={coverUrl}
        alt=""
        width={1200}
        height={630}
        class="w-full object-cover"
      />
    </figure>

    <div
      class="mt-10 space-y-4 text-pretty leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
    >
      <p>
        During the latest edition of APH, the municipality presented a case focused on the
        energy transition: how could an AI-driven platform help citizens navigate complex
        choices around sustainability — such as home insulation, energy use, and available
        subsidies — while offering tailored, understandable advice?
      </p>

      <h2
        class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200"
      >
        A policy challenge with real constraints
      </h2>
      <p>
        The challenge was not to design technology for technology's sake. Any solution
        would need to be citizen-centric and accessible, translate complex policy and
        subsidy structures into clear personal guidance, and be realistic enough to fit
        within a municipal context. Over the course of the hackathon weekend,
        interdisciplinary teams worked with data, policy constraints, and stakeholder
        input to develop proposals addressing these requirements.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="my-8 border-l-4 border-[#ff0101] pl-5 dark:border-[#ff3838]">
        <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 italic">
          "A lot of hackathons can be abstract and have no real purpose. What I
          especially liked about the municipality challenge is that there is something
          concrete behind it — a tangible impact. It's a nice example to set for other
          municipalities in the world, if it works in Amsterdam."
        </p>
        <footer class="mt-2 text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
          — Hackathon participant
        </footer>
      </blockquote>

      <h2
        class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200"
      >
        A proposal that didn't stop at the pitch
      </h2>
      <figure class="mt-10 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 dark:border-neutral-700">
        <img
          src={presentationUrl}
          alt=""
          width={1200}
          height={630}
          class="w-full object-cover"
        />
      </figure>
      <p>
        The winning team developed a concept for an AI-supported platform that would
        provide personalized energy advice, clearly linking individual actions to
        financial, environmental, and practical outcomes. Their solution also created a
        feedback loop for policymakers and analysts to learn from the needs of citizens
        engaging with the platform. Crucially, the proposal addressed not only technical
        feasibility, but also governance, transparency, and public trust.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="my-8 border-l-4 border-[#ff0101] pl-5 dark:border-[#ff3838]">
        <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 italic">
          "We didn't like the AI chatbot idea. It already exists — you can ask any
          model, people already have that. The real issue wasn't a lack of information.
          The gap is that people don't care, or they don't have the guidance to get the
          information and act on it."
        </p>
        <footer class="mt-2 text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
          — Hackathon participant
        </footer>
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        The team's solution instead aimed to meet citizens where they are: a platform
        that gives personalized guidance regardless of whether you are a homeowner or a
        renter, that doesn't feel like talking to a chatbot, and that also helps
        policymakers understand which information was lacking and which policies were
        working.
      </p>
      <p>
        What happened next is where the story becomes unusual. Following the hackathon,
        the municipality continued exploring the concept internally, and the idea moved
        into further development discussions. Rather than ending as a slide deck, the
        concept entered an active development phase within the municipal organization.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200"
      >
        The value of interdisciplinary teams
      </h2>
      <p>
        One of APH's defining features is that teams are deliberately composed across
        disciplines — bringing together students and practitioners from engineering, law,
        policy, and the social sciences. For this challenge in particular, that mix
        proved decisive.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="my-8 border-l-4 border-[#ff0101] pl-5 dark:border-[#ff3838]">
        <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 italic">
          "I was the only engineer on my team. There were people from business, law, and
          public policy. That's also a problem in other hackathons — everyone has the
          same background. Having different angles on the same problem really makes you
          think about what can realistically be done with an idea in the future."
        </p>
        <footer class="mt-2 text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
          — Hackathon participant
        </footer>
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        That cross-disciplinary dynamic also produced unexpected breakthroughs. The
        participant noted that their initial instinct was to focus on technical execution —
        building a demo website. It was a teammate from a non-technical background who
        proposed extending the platform to serve both residents and policymakers
        simultaneously — a design choice that became central to the final concept.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200"
      >
        Real feedback, in real time
      </h2>
      <p>
        Beyond teamwork, the hackathon structure itself created rare access to genuine
        stakeholder input. During the event, teams had an opportunity to receive feedback
        from a municipal contact — a moment participants found unusually grounding.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="my-8 border-l-4 border-[#ff0101] pl-5 dark:border-[#ff3838]">
        <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 italic">
          "It is very nice to get actual feedback. Often it can be abstract, especially
          for students, to get in touch with the professional side of things — to get a
          reality check. They can point out something we're missing, or guide us in a
          certain direction. It's again a mix of perspectives."
        </p>
        <footer class="mt-2 text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
          — Hackathon participant
        </footer>
      </blockquote>

      <h2
        class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200"
      >
        Momentum beyond the initial team
      </h2>
      <p>
        The concept was later presented at the municipality's office during an internal
        session attended by policymakers from multiple departments. As a result, nine
        policymakers signed up to be involved in further developing the idea, signalling
        broad internal interest and institutional ownership.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="my-8 border-l-4 border-[#ff0101] pl-5 dark:border-[#ff3838]">
        <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 italic">
          "The Amsterdam Policy Hackathon acted like an accelerator. It pushed the idea
          from something abstract to something concrete that will actually be worked on."
        </p>
        <footer class="mt-2 text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
          — Diederik Roijers, Researcher and Business Developer, Municipality of Amsterdam
        </footer>
      </blockquote>

      <h2
        class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200"
      >
        Impact for participants and education
      </h2>
      <p>
        This outcome is also a success for the participants involved. The team member
        continuing the work is a student in the MSc Complex Systems and Policy at the
        University of Amsterdam, highlighting how academic training can directly connect
        to real-world policy innovation.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="my-8 border-l-4 border-[#ff0101] pl-5 dark:border-[#ff3838]">
        <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 italic">
          "It's very much worth it if you want to work on something that can bring your
          ideas into the real world. It doesn't matter what your background is — there
          are people with very creative energy and people with a technical background,
          and they complement each other. If you're looking for something grounded and
          meaningful, I'd recommend it."
        </p>
        <footer class="mt-2 text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
          — Hackathon participant
        </footer>
      </blockquote>

      <h2
        class="mt-10 text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200"
      >
        Looking ahead
      </h2>
      <p>
        For APH, this case demonstrates the value of interdisciplinary collaboration,
        structured policy challenges, and close engagement with public-sector partners.
        It shows that hackathons, when designed carefully, can help bridge the gap
        between experimentation and implementation.
      </p>
      <p>
        As APH expands to new cities and becomes part of the broader Data for Public
        Impact Network (DPIN), this collaboration offers a concrete example of the kind
        of impact we aim to support: ideas that survive beyond the weekend and contribute
        to public value in practice.
      </p>
      <p>
        Interested in joining a future event? See{" "}
        <a
          href="/policy-hackathons/"
          class="font-medium text-[#ff0101] underline-offset-2 hover:underline dark:text-[#ff3838]"
          >policy hackathons</a
        > for hubs and announcements.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="mt-12 text-center">
      <a
        href="/blog/"
        class="text-sm font-medium text-[#ff0101] hover:underline dark:text-[#ff3838]"
        >← Back to all posts</a
      >
    </p>
  </article>
</BlogPostLayout>